---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import PrivateHeader from "../../components/PrivateHeader.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout noindex={true} title="Countering Too Ambitious | Leigh-Ann Martin" description="A drill-able playbook for defusing the fear that she is too ambitious to stay: the two real faces of the objection, six expert-backed counters with exact wording, words to avoid, and a note to Leigh-Ann.">
  <PrivateHeader />
  <div class="md:ml-60">
  <main>
    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="bg-primary pt-24 pb-12 md:pt-16 md:pb-16">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 text-center">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.2em] uppercase text-secondary mb-4">Objection Playbook</p>
        <h1 class="font-serif text-3xl md:text-4xl text-white leading-tight mb-4">
          Countering the "You're Too Ambitious to Stay" Objection
        </h1>
        <p class="text-white/55 text-base leading-relaxed max-w-xl mx-auto mb-6">
          Harris said the quiet part out loud: <span class="text-white/80 italic">"You sound like you do a lot&hellip; would you stay in this position?"</span> This fear has two faces &mdash; and both are beatable. Here is exactly how to read it, disarm it, and turn it into the reason they hire you. Built from your real record. Drill it before Sachin.
        </p>
        <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-2">
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">2 real fears, named</span>
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">6 expert counters</span>
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Exact wording</span>
          <span class="bg-white/10 border border-white/10 text-white/60 text-xs px-3 py-1 rounded-full">Words to avoid</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Quick Nav -->
    <section class="bg-primary/95 border-t border-white/[0.06] py-4 sticky top-14 md:top-0 z-40">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-2 text-xs">
          <a href="#reframe" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">Their Fear, Not Your Flaw</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#diagnose" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">The Two Real Fears</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#counters" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">The 6 Counters</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#words" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">Words to Avoid</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#questions" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">Questions to Ask</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#retention" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">The Retention Truth</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#note" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">A Note to You</a>
          <span class="text-white/15">|</span>
          <a href="#cheat" class="text-white/40 hover:text-white/70 transition-colors">30-Sec Cheat Card</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 1. Reframe First -->
    <section id="reframe" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Start Here</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-4">This Is Their Fear, Not Your Flaw</h2>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6 mb-6">
          <p class="text-primary text-base leading-relaxed">You already said the truest thing about this whole situation:</p>
          <p class="text-primary text-lg font-serif italic leading-relaxed mt-3">"That ain't got nothing to do with the candidate."</p>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mt-3">Exactly right. The anxiety in that room was there <span class="font-medium text-primary">before you walked in</span> &mdash; a great EA left after two years, the seat is stretched thin right now, and the search is bracing for a repeat. That is their wound, not your verdict. Your job is not to apologize for being capable. It is to be the calm, grounded person who makes the fear look unfounded.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-5">
            <p class="text-sm text-primary font-semibold mb-2">One exit isn't a pattern</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">The last EA stayed a <span class="font-medium text-primary">full two years</span>, then moved on. That's a normal tenure &mdash; a fact about the seat, not a prediction about you. They're treating one event like a law of nature.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-5">
            <p class="text-sm text-primary font-semibold mb-2">"You do a lot" is fear of losing you</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">That's not a criticism &mdash; it's capability they already want and are scared to lose. It's leverage. Don't shrink from it; aim it at them.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-5">
            <p class="text-sm text-primary font-semibold mb-2">A promise won't move them</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">A candidate before you reportedly promised two years and left anyway. So "I'll stay," said louder, is worthless. Only a <span class="font-medium text-primary">frame</span> plus <span class="font-medium text-primary">evidence</span> works.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 2. The Two Real Fears -->
    <section id="diagnose" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-warm">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Diagnose Before You Prescribe</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-4">The Two Real Fears Behind "Too Ambitious"</h2>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-6">Almost nobody actually fears ambition. "She's too ambitious" is the surface words for <span class="font-medium text-primary">two specific worries</span> running underneath this search. Name the right one and your counter lands; aim at the generic version and you miss.</p>

        <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-2">
              <h3 class="font-serif text-lg text-primary">Fear A &mdash; "She'll use this as a doorway."</h3>
              <span class="text-xs bg-rose-100 text-rose-700 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full whitespace-nowrap">The org's worry</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">Not that you'll quit &mdash; that you'll transfer <em>internally</em> into a different role and leave them re-hiring this seat within a year. With a transition already underway, they can't absorb a short stay.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <div class="flex items-center justify-between mb-2">
              <h3 class="font-serif text-lg text-primary">Fear B &mdash; "Will she even be content as an EA?"</h3>
              <span class="text-xs bg-rose-100 text-rose-700 px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full whitespace-nowrap">Katie's personal worry</span>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">Katie is about a month into the Chief of Staff role, running everything solo. A candidate with board governance, public-company IR, and "built it from zero" on her resume can read as a <em>threat</em>: will this person be satisfied supporting me &mdash; or angling for my seat?</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6 mb-6">
          <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-2">What they actually want</p>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-primary">
            <li><span class="font-medium">Continuity</span> &mdash; not rebuilding this seat in 12 months.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium">A return</span> on the trust and training they're about to invest.</li>
            <li><span class="font-medium">Zero disruption</span> to the executive &mdash; and, for Katie, <span class="font-medium">a partner, not a rival.</span></li>
          </ul>
          <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mt-4 pt-4 border-t border-primary/[0.06]">So stop defending your ambition. <span class="font-medium text-primary">Solve for what's underneath</span> &mdash; continuity, relief, no threat &mdash; and "too ambitious" dissolves on its own.</p>
        </div>

        <!-- The master key: two kinds of ambition -->
        <div class="bg-primary rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-7">
          <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-3">The Master Key</p>
          <h3 class="font-serif text-xl text-white mb-3">There Are Two Kinds of Ambition &mdash; Only One Scares Them</h3>
          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
            <div class="bg-white/[0.06] border border-white/10 rounded-xl p-5">
              <p class="text-white font-medium mb-1 text-sm">Ambition <span class="text-emerald-300">for impact</span></p>
              <p class="text-white/70 text-sm leading-relaxed">"I want this seat to be excellent. I want Sachin's week to run flawlessly and Katie to look great." This is the energy every executive wants beside them. <span class="text-white font-medium">Lead with it, loudly.</span></p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-white/[0.06] border border-white/10 rounded-xl p-5">
              <p class="text-white font-medium mb-1 text-sm">Ambition <span class="text-rose-300">to leave</span></p>
              <p class="text-white/70 text-sm leading-relaxed">"I'll use this as a stepping stone to something bigger." This is what they're afraid "ambitious" means. <span class="text-white font-medium">You never name it &mdash; and never accidentally signal it.</span></p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="text-white/70 text-sm leading-relaxed mt-4">You don't dial your drive down. You <span class="text-white font-medium">point the exact same drive at their outcomes.</span> That single move turns the scariest thing about you into the most reassuring.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 3. The 6 Counters -->
    <section id="counters" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">The Core</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-4">Six Ways to Counter It</h2>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-6">Six approaches from six negotiation minds. Don't memorize all six &mdash; pick the two or three that sound like <span class="font-medium text-primary">you</span> and drill those until they're reflex. Each card: the principle, when to reach for it, and exact wording grounded in your real record.</p>

        <div class="space-y-5">

          <!-- Counter 1 -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-secondary/10 text-secondary font-semibold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">1</span>
              <div>
                <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg leading-tight">Name the Fear Before They Do</h3>
                <span class="text-xs bg-primary/[0.06] text-primary px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">Chris Voss &middot; Accusation Audit + Label</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-medium text-primary">Principle:</span> say the negative thought out loud yourself, then label the emotion beneath it. Naming a fear shrinks it; ducking it confirms it. You're aiming for a quiet "that's right."</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-medium text-primary">When:</span> the instant you sense the "will she stay?" hesitation &mdash; or proactively, right after you've described how much you've carried.</p>
            <div class="bg-secondary/5 rounded-lg p-4 mb-3">
              <p class="text-sm text-primary font-medium mb-1">Say this:</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"Let me name what might be in the back of your mind. With everything I've taken on, part of you may wonder if I'll get restless and use this as a stepping stone &mdash; especially after the last person moved on. That's fair to wonder."</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-secondary/5 rounded-lg p-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-primary font-medium mb-1">Then label, and stop talking:</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"It sounds like what you need most right now is someone who's going to stay and steady this seat." <span class="not-italic text-text-muted/70">&mdash; then let the silence do the work.</span></p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Counter 2 -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-secondary/10 text-secondary font-semibold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">2</span>
              <div>
                <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg leading-tight">Give Them Permission to Say No</h3>
                <span class="text-xs bg-primary/[0.06] text-primary px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">Jim Camp &middot; Start With No</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-medium text-primary">Principle:</span> neediness is what they're scanning for. Hand them the right to reject you and the desperation vanishes &mdash; which is precisely when they relax and trust you.</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-medium text-primary">When:</span> the moment you feel yourself starting to over-sell or "go through all the things." Do the opposite.</p>
            <div class="bg-secondary/5 rounded-lg p-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-primary font-medium mb-1">Say this:</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"I want to be the last person you hire for this seat, not the next one. So if anything here makes you feel I'm a flight risk, I'd rather you tell me no than take a chance &mdash; I'm not interested in talking you into something we'd both regret."</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Counter 3 -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-secondary/10 text-secondary font-semibold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">3</span>
              <div>
                <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg leading-tight">The "One Bad Date" Reframe</h3>
                <span class="text-xs bg-primary/[0.06] text-primary px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">Reframing &middot; Past &ne; Future</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-medium text-primary">Principle:</span> they're generalizing from one experience. Expose the logic gently &mdash; one ending isn't a verdict on whoever comes next &mdash; then replace the fear with your record before they can re-grip it.</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-medium text-primary">When:</span> when the conversation keeps circling "the last person." Keep it warm and human, never a debate.</p>
            <div class="bg-secondary/5 rounded-lg p-4 mb-3">
              <p class="text-sm text-primary font-medium mb-1">Say this:</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"The last EA moving on stung &mdash; I get it. But one departure is a single data point, not a pattern. None of us swears off relationships after one breakup. The real question isn't whether someone left before; it's whether the person in front of you has a record of staying."</p>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-primary/[0.03] rounded-lg p-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-primary font-medium mb-1">Then pivot straight to the receipt:</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm">"I was at Immunovant three years &mdash; the sole EA scaling support from one executive to five C-suite leaders. I don't job-hop. I embed, and I stay to run what I build."</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Counter 4 -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-secondary/10 text-secondary font-semibold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">4</span>
              <div>
                <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg leading-tight">Separate the Position From the Interest</h3>
                <span class="text-xs bg-primary/[0.06] text-primary px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">Fisher &amp; Ury &middot; Getting to Yes</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-medium text-primary">Principle:</span> their <em>position</em> ("we want someone who won't leave") hides their real <em>interest</em> ("never rebuild this seat again"). Solve the interest and the position stops mattering.</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-medium text-primary">When:</span> when you want to sound like a problem-solver, not a defendant. It moves you from "risk" to "partner."</p>
            <div class="bg-secondary/5 rounded-lg p-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-primary font-medium mb-1">Say this:</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"I don't think the real worry is ambition &mdash; it's disruption. You don't want to be re-hiring this role next year. So let's solve that directly: I document the seat as I build it, so the knowledge lives in the system, not just in me. You get continuity either way &mdash; and a year in, I'm the reason this office runs without you thinking about it."</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Counter 5 -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-secondary/10 text-secondary font-semibold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">5</span>
              <div>
                <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg leading-tight">Be the Prize, Not the Petitioner</h3>
                <span class="text-xs bg-primary/[0.06] text-primary px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">Oren Klaff &middot; Pitch Anything</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-medium text-primary">Principle:</span> control the frame by flipping who's choosing whom. Treat this like pitching a $150K client on working with you. Selectivity reads as value &mdash; your deliberate walk-aways are proof you commit slowly and stay long.</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-medium text-primary">When:</span> when the power tilts toward them and your confidence wobbles. This resets the room without a trace of arrogance.</p>
            <div class="bg-secondary/5 rounded-lg p-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-primary font-medium mb-1">Say this:</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"I'm selective too &mdash; I've turned down seats that weren't the right fit. I'm not looking for a job; I'm looking for the principal and the org I plant in. The fact that I choose this carefully is exactly why, once I commit, I don't leave."</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Counter 6 -->
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-3">
              <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-secondary/10 text-secondary font-semibold text-sm flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">6</span>
              <div>
                <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary text-lg leading-tight">Proof Over Promise</h3>
                <span class="text-xs bg-primary/[0.06] text-primary px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">Cialdini &middot; Influence</span>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-medium text-primary">Principle:</span> commitment and consistency persuade; promises don't. Agree with their skepticism first &mdash; it disarms them &mdash; then hand over evidence they can't argue with.</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3"><span class="font-medium text-primary">When:</span> as your closer on this topic. It's the most disarming counter because it starts on their side of the table.</p>
            <div class="bg-secondary/5 rounded-lg p-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-primary font-medium mb-1">Say this:</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"I could promise I'll stay for years &mdash; but I'd guess the last candidate said that too, so why should it mean anything from me? Don't take my word. Take my record: three years at Immunovant, sole EA to five C-suite. At Ascend I built the board cadence from zero and earned the chairman's direct line over twelve months. I don't talk about loyalty &mdash; I have a track record of it."</p>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 4. Words to Avoid -->
    <section id="words" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-warm">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Don't Hand Them the Fear</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-4">Words That Trigger the Fear &mdash; and What to Say Instead</h2>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-6">The best counters in the world won't matter if a single careless phrase confirms Fear A or Fear B. When the "where do you see yourself?" question comes, the goal is to read as <span class="font-medium text-primary">committed to mastering this seat</span> &mdash; never eyeing the next jump.</p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-6">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-rose-700 mb-3">Don't say</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted">
              <li>"I'd love to grow into a Chief of Staff role here." <span class="text-text-muted/70">(reads as: I want her seat)</span></li>
              <li>"This is a great way to get into Amex." <span class="text-text-muted/70">(reads as: stepping stone)</span></li>
              <li>"In five years I'd want to be in [another role]." <span class="text-text-muted/70">(reads as: flight risk)</span></li>
              <li>"I'm open to wherever the company takes me." <span class="text-text-muted/70">(reads as: I'll drift off)</span></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6">
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-emerald-700 mb-3">Say instead (make it yours)</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-text-muted">
              <li>"My aspiration is to be the person Sachin and Katie never have to think about &mdash; to know the seat so well it just runs."</li>
              <li>"Success for me is becoming indispensable in <em>this</em> role &mdash; the org, the rhythms, the relationships, cold."</li>
              <li>"I want a seat I can settle into and master, not pass through."</li>
              <li>"I want to grow <em>deeper</em> in the role &mdash; more trusted, more anticipatory &mdash; not out of it."</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-secondary/5 border border-secondary/15 rounded-xl p-5">
          <p class="text-sm text-primary"><span class="font-semibold">One guardrail:</span> <span class="text-text-muted">don't pre-script this word-for-word &mdash; over-rehearsed commitment language sounds defensive, like you're answering an accusation. Hold the posture (<em>depth, mastery, making them look great, here for the long run</em>) and let the sentence come out fresh. If aspirations never come up, plant it once, lightly: "Just so it's clear &mdash; I'm looking for a seat to settle into, not pass through."</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 5. Questions to Ask -->
    <section id="questions" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-cream">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Hand Them the Problem</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-4">Calibrated Questions to Ask Back</h2>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mb-6">Voss-style "How" and "What" questions flip the burden: instead of you defending, <span class="font-medium text-primary">they</span> define what staying means &mdash; and feel in control while doing it. Drop one in when the worry surfaces.</p>

        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-5">
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"What would I need to show you in the first year for you to feel certain I'm here for the long haul?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted/70 text-xs mt-2">Makes them name the success criteria &mdash; then you meet it on purpose.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-5">
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"How do you see the EA and Chief of Staff roles dividing ownership? I want to complement what you do, not duplicate it."</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted/70 text-xs mt-2">Defuses Fear B directly &mdash; signals partner, not rival, without ever naming the threat.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-5">
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"How do you picture this role growing for the right person over the next few years?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted/70 text-xs mt-2">Reframes ambition as something the seat can <em>absorb</em> &mdash; so staying and growing stop competing.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-5">
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"Would it be a crazy idea that someone can be both genuinely driven and genuinely loyal?"</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted/70 text-xs mt-2">A "no"-oriented question &mdash; "no, that's not crazy" feels safe to say and quietly concedes your whole point.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 6. The Retention Truth -->
    <section id="retention" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-warm">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">For Your Confidence</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-4">The Retention Truth &mdash; and How to Use It</h2>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6 mb-5">
          <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">Hold this quietly in your back pocket: <span class="font-medium text-primary">if a seat keeps emptying out, that's an organizational signal &mdash; not proof the next person is a flight risk.</span> A strong EA leaving, and the seat now stretched thin, says more about the role and the support around it than about anyone who's held it. So walk in steady. You are not the suspect here. If anything, <span class="font-medium text-primary">they</span> have something to prove to <span class="font-medium text-primary">you</span> &mdash; and the urgency of their need is your leverage, not your weakness.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-2xl p-6 mb-5">
          <p class="text-sm text-amber-900 font-semibold mb-2">But don't lecture them on retention.</p>
          <p class="text-amber-900/80 text-sm leading-relaxed">"Your retention is the real problem" may be true, but it reads as combative and puts their ego on the line. Convert the insight into one warm question that surfaces it <em>and</em> signals your intent to stay.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-emerald-200 p-5">
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-emerald-700 mb-2">Say this</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"What led the last person to move on? I want to make sure I'm stepping into something I can genuinely commit to long-term."</p>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-red-200 p-5">
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-red-700 mb-2">Not this</p>
            <p class="text-text-muted text-sm italic">"If people keep leaving, maybe the issue is what the company is doing about retention, not the candidates."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed mt-5">That one question does triple duty: it gets you real intel on whether this seat is survivable, it casts you as someone <em>planning</em> to stay, and it puts retention on the table &mdash; without you ever pointing a finger.</p>

        <!-- The Bold Move -->
        <div class="bg-primary rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-7 mt-8 border-2 border-secondary">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3">
            <span class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary">The Bold Move</span>
            <span class="text-[10px] font-bold tracking-wider uppercase bg-secondary/20 text-secondary px-2 py-0.5 rounded-full">Use when you have leverage</span>
          </div>
          <h3 class="font-serif text-xl text-white mb-3">Flip It: Make Them Sell <span class="italic">You</span> on Staying</h3>
          <p class="text-white/70 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">If the room keeps circling the fear of people leaving &mdash; and you can feel you're in a position of strength (Sachin already preferred your resume; you have options) &mdash; turn it around. Done warmly, this is the single most powerful move on this page: it stops you defending yourself and makes <span class="text-white font-medium">them</span> defend the role. Suddenly they're recruiting you, and a candidate worth recruiting reads as a candidate worth keeping.</p>

          <div class="bg-white/[0.06] border border-white/10 rounded-xl p-5 mb-4">
            <p class="text-secondary text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Say this (curious, not accusatory)</p>
            <p class="text-white/85 text-sm italic leading-relaxed mb-3">"I'll be honest &mdash; I'm hearing a real focus on whether someone will stay, and I want to understand it, because I'm planning to. So let me ask you a few things:"</p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-white/80">
              <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-secondary flex-shrink-0">&rarr;</span> "Has this happened before &mdash; is turnover in this seat a one-time thing, or a pattern?"</li>
              <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-secondary flex-shrink-0">&rarr;</span> "Is it specific to this role, or are other positions on the team and in the department seeing the same thing?"</li>
              <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-secondary flex-shrink-0">&rarr;</span> "When people have moved on, what's usually driven it &mdash; the comp, the growth path, the day-to-day?"</li>
              <li class="flex gap-2"><span class="text-secondary flex-shrink-0">&rarr;</span> "And what's the team doing to make people <em>want</em> to stay &mdash; what makes someone thrive here for the long run?"</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <p class="text-white/70 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">Then close it by putting your intention right back on the table: <span class="text-white/90 italic">"I ask because I'm not looking to land somewhere and leave &mdash; I'm looking for the seat I plant in. I just want to make sure this is one I can commit to for years, and it sounds like you want the same thing."</span></p>

          <div class="bg-amber-400/10 border border-amber-300/30 rounded-xl p-4">
            <p class="text-amber-200 text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-1">Read the room first</p>
            <p class="text-white/70 text-sm leading-relaxed">Only deploy this once rapport is warm and you sense real interest &mdash; ideally later in the process, not a first screen. Deliver it with a genuine smile and an even, curious tone: you're doing your due diligence, not issuing a challenge. If their answers are vague or defensive, that's your red flag. If they light up and sell you, you've just turned the whole conversation in your favor.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 7. A Note to You -->
    <section id="note" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-primary">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Read This When the Doubt Creeps In</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-white mb-6">A Note to You, Leigh-Ann</h2>
        <div class="bg-white/[0.04] border border-white/10 rounded-2xl p-6 md:p-8 space-y-4">
          <p class="text-white/80 text-base leading-relaxed">You diagnosed this perfectly on your own: <span class="text-white italic">"that ain't got nothing to do with the candidate."</span> Trust that &mdash; it's sharper than the doubt that's been circling since the Harris call. The comment that "messed with you" wasn't a knock. "You sound like you do a lot" is what people say right before they realize they can't afford to lose you.</p>
          <p class="text-white/80 text-base leading-relaxed">Doing a lot is not a flaw to apologize for. It is the reason <span class="text-white">Sachin pulled your resume out of six.</span> You don't need to shrink to make them comfortable &mdash; you need to make it unmistakable that all that capability is aimed straight at making their lives easier, and that you're someone who stays and builds. You've already proven it: three years at Immunovant, building Ascend's board cadence from nothing and earning the chairman's direct line. People who flee don't leave records like that.</p>
          <p class="text-white/80 text-base leading-relaxed">You can't control whether they get out of their own way and see what's in front of them. You can only control how grounded you are when you walk in. So go in steady. You're not auditioning for permission to be ambitious &mdash; you're deciding whether <em>they</em> are worth planting in. As you said: if it's for you, it's for you. Walk in like it already is.</p>
          <p class="text-white/50 text-sm pt-2">&mdash; Your prep team</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 8. Cheat Card -->
    <section id="cheat" class="py-12 md:py-16 bg-warm">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6">
        <p class="text-secondary text-xs font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-2">Re-read 5 Minutes Before</p>
        <h2 class="font-serif text-2xl md:text-3xl text-primary mb-6">The 30-Second Cheat Card</h2>
        <div class="bg-white rounded-2xl shadow-sm border border-primary/[0.06] p-6 space-y-5">
          <div>
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-1">The one line to land</p>
            <p class="text-primary text-sm leading-relaxed italic">"I'm driven &mdash; about <span class="font-medium not-italic">your</span> outcomes. That energy goes into the seat, not past it. I build for the long run, not the next step."</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-1">If the worry surfaces, in order</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1.5 text-sm text-text-muted">
              <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">1. Name it</span> (Voss): "Part of you may wonder if I'll use this as a stepping stone&hellip;"</li>
              <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">2. Proof, not promise</span> (Cialdini): "Three years at Immunovant, sole EA to five C-suite."</li>
              <li><span class="font-medium text-primary">3. Hand them the question</span>: "What would I need to show you in year one?"</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-1">Never say</p>
            <p class="text-primary text-sm leading-relaxed">"Grow into Chief of Staff," "get into Amex," "in five years I'd be in [other role]." Replace with <span class="font-medium">depth, mastery, indispensable in this seat.</span></p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-1">Delivery</p>
            <p class="text-primary text-sm leading-relaxed">Slow down by a third. Headline first, then one example, then stop. When you feel the urge to "go through all the things," that's your cue to ask a question instead.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase text-secondary mb-1">Remember</p>
            <p class="text-primary text-sm leading-relaxed">This is their fear, not your flaw. You're not the risk in the room &mdash; you're the answer to it.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-muted/60 text-xs mt-6">See also the shorter version of this objection in your <a href={`${base}private/interview-prep#objections`} class="text-secondary hover:underline">Interview Prep Guide</a> and the cheat card in your <a href={`${base}private/amex-katie-interview`} class="text-secondary hover:underline">Amex / Katie prep</a>.</p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
  </div>
</Layout>

<script>
  const revealEls = document.querySelectorAll("[data-reveal], [data-reveal-stagger]");
  const observer = new IntersectionObserver(
    (entries) => {
      entries.forEach((entry) => {
        if (entry.isIntersecting) {
          entry.target.classList.add("revealed");
          observer.unobserve(entry.target);
        }
      });
    },
    { threshold: 0.1, rootMargin: "0px 0px -60px 0px" }
  );
  revealEls.forEach((el) => observer.observe(el));
</script>
